<section xml:id="sec-pop-models-and-leslie-matrices" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Population models and Leslie matrices</title>

  <p> 
  We study the female population of some species divided into <m>n</m> ages groups
  of equal duration. We let
  <ul>
    <li>
      <p>
        <m>x_i</m> be the population of age group <m>i</m>,
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        <m>b_i</m> be how many (female) offspring each of the <m>x_i</m> has,
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        <m>s_i</m> be the survival rate of age group <m>i</m>, and
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        <m>\vect{x}_m=\begin{bmatrix}x_1\\\vdots\\x_n\end{bmatrix}_m</m> be the 
        population vector at time <m>m</m>. 
      </p>
    </li>
  </ul>
  </p>

  <p>
    <term>Question:</term> What will the populations be at time <m>m+1</m>?
  </p>

  <p>
    The populations at time <m>m+1</m> will be 
    <ul>
  <li>Group 1: <m>b_1x_1 + b_2x_2 + \cdots + b_nx_n</m></li>
  <li>Group 2: <m>s_1x_1</m></li>
  <li>Group 3: <m>s_2x_2</m></li>
</ul>

<p><m>\qquad\qquad\qquad\vdots</m></p>

<ul>
  <li>Group <m>n</m>: <m>s_{n-1}x_{n-1}</m>.</li>
</ul>
  </p>

  <p>
  We think of this process as a linear transformation <m>\R^n\to\R^n</m> given by
  <md>
    \begin{bmatrix}x_1\\x_2\\\vdots\\x_n\end{bmatrix}_m\mapsto \begin{bmatrix}
    b_1x_1+\cdots +b_nx_n\\ s_1x_1\\\vdots\\s_{n-1}x_{n-1}\end{bmatrix}_{m+1}.
  </md>
  The associated matrix of this linear transformation 
  <md>
    L=\begin{bmatrix} b_1 \amp b_2\amp b_3 \amp \cdots \amp b_{n-1} \amp b_n\\
    s_1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp \cdots \amp 0 \amp 0\\
    0 \amp s_2 \amp  0 \amp \cdots \amp 0 \amp 0\\
    \vdots \amp \vdots \amp \ddots \amp \ddots \amp \vdots \amp \vdots\\
    0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp \cdots \amp s_{n-1} \amp 0
    \end{bmatrix}
  </md>
  is called a <m>Leslie matrix</m> (named after Patrick Leslie, who was a 
  Scottish physiologist best known for his work on population dynamics).
  </p>

  <p>
    We present the following facts about Leslie matrices without proof. You will prove some 
    of these results in tutorials; others are not so obvious.
  </p>

<p>
  <term>Facts about Leslie matrices:</term>
    <ul>

      <li>
        <p>
         Every Leslie matrix has a unique positive eigenvalue <m>\lambda_m</m>. This eigenvalue
         <m>\lambda_m</m> has algebraic and geometric multiplicity 1, and has a corresponding 
         eigenvector that can be written with positive components. 
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
         If two consecutive birth rates are positive (ie. there is some <m>i</m> with
         <m>b_i,b_{i+1}>0</m>), then for all other eigenvalues <m>\lambda</m> of <m>L</m>
         we have <m> | \lambda | &lt; \lambda_m </m>.
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
         We have 
         <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\lambda_m=1\implies</m> populations stabilise,
            </p>
          </li> 

          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\lambda_m &gt; 1\implies</m> populations grow to infinity, and
            </p>
          </li> 

          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\lambda_m &lt; 1\implies</m> populations fall to zero.
            </p>
          </li> 
        </ul>
        </p>
      </li>
    
       <li>
        <p>
          If two consecutive birth rates are positive, then the ratio of populations stabilise
          in the ratio of the components of an eigenvector for <m>\lambda_m</m>. 
        </p>
      </li>
      
    </ul>
  </p>

<example xml:id="ex-leslie-matrix">
<statement>
<p>
Consider the Leslie matrix
<md>
  L=\begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 2 \amp 16\\
  0.5 \amp 0 \amp 0\\
  0 \amp 0.25 \amp 0
  \end{bmatrix}.
</md>
Check carefully, or use an online calculator, to verify the following:
<ul>
  <li>
    <p>
     <m>\lambda_m=2</m> is the unique positive eigenvalue. 
    </p>
  </li>

  <li>
    <p>
      <m>[32,8,1]</m> is an eigenvector for <m>\lambda_m=1</m>.
    </p>
  </li>

  <li>
    <p>
      We have
      <md>
        \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 2 \amp 16\\
  0.5 \amp 0 \amp 0\\
  0 \amp 0.25 \amp 0
  \end{bmatrix}^{10}\begin{bmatrix}1\\1\\1\end{bmatrix}=\begin{bmatrix}6443\\1606.5\\201\end{bmatrix}
  \sim \begin{bmatrix}6400\\1600\\200\end{bmatrix}=200\begin{bmatrix}32\\8\\1\end{bmatrix},
      </md>
     which illustrates the long-term behaviour of how the ratios of populations behave. 
    </p>
  </li>
</ul>
</p>
</statement>
</example>
</section>